Case Study: How Does a Bike-Share Navigate Speedy Success?

Vlad Bularca

06/10/2021

Overview

Scenario

You are a junior data analyst working in the marketing analyst team at Cyclistic, a bike-share company in Chicago. The director of marketing believes the company’s future success depends on maximizing the number of annual memberships. Therefore, your team wants to understand how casual riders and annual members use Cyclistic bikes differently. From these insights, your team will design a new marketing strategy to convert casual riders into annual members. But first, Cyclistic executives must approve your recommendations, so they must be backed up with compelling data insights and professional data visualizations.

About the Company

Until now, Cyclistic’s marketing strategy relied on building general awareness and appealing to broad consumer segments. One approach that helped make these things possible was the flexibility of its pricing plans: single-ride passes, full-day passes, and annual memberships. Customers who purchase single-ride or full-day passes are referred to as casual riders. Customers who purchase annual memberships are Cyclistic members.

Cyclistic’s finance analysts have concluded that annual members are much more profitable than casual riders. Lily Moreno, the Director of Marketing, believes that there is a very good chance to convert casual riders into members, as opposed to creating a marketing campaign that targets all-new customers. She notes that casual riders are already aware of the Cyclistic program and have chosen Cyclistic for their mobility needs.

Moreno has set a clear goal: Design marketing strategies aimed at converting casual riders into annual members. In order to do that, however, the marketing analyst team needs to better understand how annual members and casual riders differ, why casual riders would buy a membership, and how digital media could affect their marketing tactics. Moreno and her team are interested in analyzing the Cyclistic historical bike trip data to identify trends.

My Responsibilities

In this scenario, I am a Junior Data Analyst that will use the data provided by the company to find out how casual riders and members use the service differently and how these insights can be used to develop a campaign and create a data driven marketing strategy by the marketing analyst team.

I will be documenting my entire work process in this file, showing how I cleaned and processed the data and then used it to generate insights and develop recommendations so that the company can achieve its goals moving forward.

Data Source

The Data used for this project was Cyclisitc’s historical trip data. The previous 12 months of trip data are available publicly: https://divvy-tripdata.s3.amazonaws.com/index.html

The data set I used is composed of 12 monthly data files that make up a year of bike share trips . I started by analyzing each of the monthly files using Excel, to see if I could process, check the integrity of the data and clean it before analyzing it further using R.

Important Questions

What do I need to get from the data and what questions should I ask to achieve this? * The stop with the most non-members - The stop with the most members in general (both starting and finishing) - The difference in how often members use the service - How far each member travels, the average? - And how long each member is travelling for. - Percentage of member and casuals based on month, day of the week and time?

Data Processing and Cleaning

When I first opened the CSV files in Excel, I noticed the large number of rows, ranging from 80,00 to 700,000 rows per month. The large size of the files made Excel slow, but I was able to make sense of the data and clean it. My cleaning steps included:

  • Deleting rows that had important information missing. I actually had to upload the CSV files to BigQuery because some of the files were to large for excel to process. I was able to remove rows with blanks using “DELETE FROM”
  • Making sure the format was consistent throughout each column
  • Creating a new column called “ride_length” which calculated the time difference between the start of each ride and the end of each ride, to see how long each ride was
  • Creating a new column called “day_of_week” to find out what day of the week each trip was taken on - Deleting all rows containing a ride_length of 0:00:00 (Most of these were test rides)
  • Deleting all rows containing a negative value for ride_length
  • Replacing faulty station_name labels with “Find & Replace” using the corresponding station_ID and matching the station_name using the data from other months

The 12 CSV files containing monthly data were now ready to be analyzed using R.

Changing the start and end station id column types from integer to character so that bind_rows doesn’t produce an error.

sept20$start_station_id <-as.character(sept20$start_station_id)
sept20$end_station_id <-as.character(sept20$start_station_id)

oct20$start_station_id <-as.character(oct20$start_station_id)
oct20$end_station_id <-as.character(oct20$start_station_id)

nov20$start_station_id <-as.character(nov20$start_station_id)
nov20$end_station_id <-as.character(nov20$start_station_id)

Combining all of the data into one table:

year_data <- bind_rows(sept20, oct20, nov20, dec20, jan21, 
feb21, mar21, apr21, may21, june21, july21, aug21)

Total number of rides after combining the 12 CSV files to get a full years perspective:

nrow(year_data)
## [1] 4226673

There are 4,226,673 total rides.

Extracting the date from the ‘started_at’ column and putting it into a new column named ‘date’ so I can use it for analysis:

year_data$date <- as.Date(year_data$started_at)

Splitting the ’date" column into respective day, year and month columns to easily access different these different parameters and use them to see differences between members and casual riders.

year_data$day <- format(as.Date(year_data$date), "%d")
year_data$month <- format(as.Date(year_data$date), "%m")
year_data$year <- format(as.Date(year_data$date), "%Y")

I also made 2 columns that reflect the start hour and end hour for each ride:

year_data$start_hour <- lubridate::hour(year_data$started_at)
year_data$end_hour <- lubridate::hour(year_data$ended_at)

The ride_length was recognized as a character, but it needs to be a numeric value so I converted it:

year_data$ride_length <- chron(times=year_data$ride_length)

is.numeric(year_data$ride_length)
## [1] TRUE
# is.numeric checks to see the data type of column ride_length
